ts as they did from activists. Through theoretical and archival work, Love traces the connection between midcentury studies of deviance and the anti-normative, anti-essentialist field of queer theory. While sociologists saw deviance as an inevitable fact of social life, queer theorists embraced it as a rallying cry. A robust interdisciplinary history of the field, Underdogs stages a reencounter with the practices and communities that underwrite radical queer thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aDeviant behaviorxResearchzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aQueer theoryxHistory. 0aSociologyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  amarginal, communities, stonewall, sociology, outsiders, movements, activist, humanities, gender, sexual, norms, interdisciplinary, radical, thought.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226761244423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226761244/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles